ABOUT EU LCS

ABOUT EU LCS

The League of Legends Championship Series (LCS) is the preeminent League of Legends esports league in North America and Europe. The EU LCS is comprised of 10 teams drafted into two groups of 5 teams. Each team plays the teams in their group twice, and the teams in the opposing group once, for a total of 13 matches per split. The competition stretches across two splits, Spring and Summer. Starting with the 2017 EU LCS Spring Split, matches will be played in a Best of 3 format. Read more about the format changes here.

Teams were drafted into their groups via a special selection process. Based on their championship points totals during the 2016 EU LCS season, G2 Esports and H2K took the first and second seed at the head of each group. Groups were then selected via snake draft, similar to a Nemesis draft. Instead of drafting teams into their own group, the team picking chose a team to go into the opposing group rather than their own. The following graphic illustrates the process.


Tiebreakers:

  • If two teams have the same record, ties will be broken by Head to Head record
  • If Head to Head records are identical, total games won will be used.
  • If still tied, a tiebreaker match will be played.

For complete tiebreaker scenarios, view the full rules page.

Playoff Format:

LCS playoffs are comprised of six teams in a seeded, single elimination tournament. All matches are Best of 5 format. A third/fourth place match is played.

Championship points

Starting with the 2015 LCS season, NA and EU leagues will utilize Championship Points (otherwise known to some as circuit points) for World Championship qualification. The Championship Point system ensures that teams always play their best and allows for better alignment with other international leagues.

Here’s how an LCS team qualifies for Worlds:

  • 1st place team of the Summer Split will automatically qualify (AQ) for Worlds as the first seed from that region.
  • The team that has accrued the most championship points throughout the season will also qualify for Worlds as the second seed.
  • In the event that multiple teams are tied in the standings at the conclusion of the Summer Split, then the team that gained the most points in the Summer Split will be considered the holder of the tiebreaker.
  • The final spot for Worlds will be determined at the NA and EU Regional Qualifiers, the winners of which will be the third seeds of their respective regions.

Points will be awarded in the following way:

Place Spring Split Summer Split
1st 90 AQ
2nd 70 90
3rd 50 70
4th 30 40
5th-6th 10 20
7th-10th 0 0

 

How to watch

You can attend matches live every week at the EU LCS studio in Berlin, Germany. Click on the "Tickets" tab for more information on seeing the LCS in person. You can also watch the LCS live every week on lolesports or on our spoiler-free vods page once the match is finished.

LCS RULES - INTRODUCTION AND PURPOSE

These official rules of the League of Legends Championship Series LLC apply to each of the Teams who have qualified to play in the EU LCS or EU CS in 2017, or are participating in one of their Qualifiers. These rules also apply to the Teams’ Team Managers & Team Members and other employees but apply only to official League play and not to other competitions, tournaments or organized play of League of Legends.

League of Legends Championship Series LLC, a Delaware limited liability company, has established these rules for the competitive play of League of Legends in order to unify and standardize the rules used in competitive play.

These official rules are designed solely to ensure the integrity of the system established by the League for professional play of League of Legends and a competitive balance among the Teams that play at the professional level. Standardized rules benefit all parties who are involved in the professional play of League of Legends, including the Team Managers, Team Members and Teams. Rules that impact all regions can be seen in the Global Rules section.

The terms of engagement between Team Managers, Team Members and Teams are left to each of the Teams and its Team Manager/Members.

The complete LCS Rules document can be downloaded here.

The EU Rulebook covers the entirety of Riot-sanctioned League play in Europe. A changelog which outlines all modifications to the ruleset can be viewed here.

INTERREGIONAL ANTI-POACHING AND ANTI-TAMPERING POLICY

 

What is the interregional anti-poaching and anti-tampering policy?

No team member or affiliate of a team may engage in the solicitation, luring, or discussion of employment of a player who is under a league-recognized contract with a professional team competing in the top-level league of a region. Similarly, players under league-recognized contracts cannot solicit or reach out directly to other team members or affiliates of other teams. In the event of prolonged discussions of employment that aren't sanctioned by the management of both teams, both the party attempting to poach and the player being poached will be subject to penalties at the discretion of league officials.

Should any interested team wish to engage in conversation with a player under a league-recognized contract with another team, they must first contact the management of the team holding the contract.

League Notification: 

After the teams have come to an agreement and before initiating contact between the interested team and player of interest, they must notify their respective regional office of the agreement, with confirmation from both teams' management via email.

Prospective teams and team affiliates (owners seeking to enter a league, etc.) attempting to poach players will also be subject to sanctions, up to and including denial of entry into Riot-sanctioned leagues and competitive events.

If I'm interested in acquiring a player, how do I know if he or she is currently under contract?

As a team, you can inquire about the availability of players - it just needs to be to the player's management so long as that player is under contract.

The database linked above contains the contract end-dates of contracted players currently participating in leagues where there are league-recognized contracts (i.e., contracts that conform with league minimum standards, such as minimum player compensation). It also includes contact information for teams who have volunteered contact information. It will be updated at the beginning of every split and periodically during the split to reflect roster modifications.

This database is intended as a resource to facilitate legitimate communication between teams and players. Where there is good reason to believe a player is under a league-recognized contract despite not being in the database (e.g. a brand new player in a league with officially-recognized contracts not yet having his or her information reflected in the database), teams are expected to contact management rather than approach players directly.

If I'm a contracted player interested in leaving my team, what are my options?

While contracted players cannot reach out to other teams' affiliates, they can:

  • Publicly state their interest in leaving their team and encourage any and all interested party to contact their management.
  • Players cannot encourage specific teams, publicly or privately, to reach out to their management.
  • Exercise a buyout clause in their contract to leave their team if one exists.
  • Reach out to teams once their contract expires (typically during the off-season for most players).

Clarification of restrictions:

  • Teams and affiliates of those teams cannot engage in discussions with players under contract regarding potential employment.
  • Teams are to reach out to other teams directly regarding employment of contracted players.
  • Players under contract with a team should not engage in employment discussion directly with other teams.
  • Players not under contract are free to reach out to potential employers and vice-versa.

Why do you have the current poaching policy?

Poaching protections are important both for the stability of organizations and to avoid competitive integrity issues. During the season, it's important that players aren't being distracted from their preparation or being tempted to play at less than 100% by offers of employment from rival teams.

When players and teams sign a contract they are entering into an agreement that a player will play for a team during a defined period of time and be duly compensated for their play - players abruptly dissolving their contracts due to employment discussions with other teams during the season creates a chaotic environment for teams and players and undermines the stability of the competitive ecosystem.

This doesn't mean that we want to prevent players from ever switching teams or finding the team that is the best fit for them - discussing the possibility of being traded to another team with their management, or simply waiting until their current contract is up before engaging in any negotiation they want. For players whose contract includes a buyout clause, that's an option they may be able to exercise as well. Ultimately, the value of contracts goes both ways. For players, contracts provide stability and the promise of a paycheck. For teams, contracts guarantee that contracted players play for their team and if a player wants to leave a team, the team management are a necessary part of that discussion. This is an important dynamic to preserve, and poaching protections are one way of doing so.

INTERREGIONAL MOVEMENT POLICY

1.2 REGIONAL RESIDENCY REQUIREMENT & WORK ELIGIBILITY

a) Resident Defined. For purposes of this Rule 1.2, a player is deemed to be a "Resident" of a region if such player has legally resided and been primarily present in such region for no less than twenty-four months out of the thirty-six months immediately prior to such players' participation in the first game of the applicable tournament (i.e., a match in the World Championship Event, LCS, or Challenger Series).

In defining a Resident, we sought to create a policy that defines Residents based on sustained and prolonged presence with a region, rather than citizenship or legal documentation. This policy makes sure that Residents not only have resided in the region whose league they wish to play in for a substantial period of time, it also gives every player the option of becoming a Resident for that league after a prolonged commitment. We used the language “primarily present” so that a reasonable amount of discretion can be used in allowing for vacations and other such temporary travel when considering eligibility.

b) Certification of Residency. All players shall certify their residency upon participation in the World Championship Event, the NA and EU LCS, and the NA and EU Challenger Series by submitting an eligibility form, and providing proof of residency as defined in Rules 1.2(c) and (d). Each team is responsible for ensuring that its players meet the residency requirements in this Rule 1.2. It shall be a violation of these Rules, by both the team and the player, if a player (or his or her parent or guardian) provides false, misleading or incomplete information resulting in the misclassification of such player’s residency and region. A violation of this Rule 1.2 by a team or a player shall also be deemed a violation of Rule 10.2, and the disciplinary measures in Rules 10.5 and 10.6 shall apply.

c) Proof of Residency. Any player over eighteen years of age may prove residency by the provision of documentary evidence sufficient to demonstrate actual residence in the region in which he or she wishes to play. Such documentary evidence may be in the form of one or more examples of:

  • i. Government Issued Documentation. A player may prove residency by providing copies of a driver’s license, voter registration form, vehicle registration, government benefits records, military or draft registration papers or other government-issued records or identification that demonstrate residency.
  • ii. Private Documentation. A player may prove residency by providing copies of school records, deeds, leases, homeowners association documents, utility bills (such as gas, water, electricity, cable, or telephone, provided that all show levels of use consistent with actual residency), bank records and statements, tax returns, insurance documents, medical records and employment records.
    •

d) Residency of Minors. Players who are below eighteen years of age may prove residency by either:

  • i. School Records. A player may prove residency by providing proof of full-time attendance at school in the region, including by providing copies of report cards, enrollment documentation, or attendance records certified by school officials; or
  • ii. Parents’ Records. A player may prove residency by (i) providing documentary evidence of the parent-child relationship, such as a birth certificate that lists the names of parents, and (ii) proof that one parent lives in the region, which may be demonstrated by provision of documentary evidence sufficient to prove residency as specified in Rule 1.2(c), above.
    •

Proving that a player has resided in a region for two out of the last three years can be a somewhat tricky process, so we’ve given categories of documentation that can help establish a player’s Resident status. This is ultimately a process that relies on making good judgment calls, but by permitting numerous categories of proof we can ensure that no player is left without options. We’ll be increasing the timeframe during which a team should submit its paperwork to register a roster change to make sure each change can be assessed within a reasonable period of time, and working with teams to collect paperwork that is acceptable for each circumstance.

e) Starters. For purposes of Rule 1.2, as stated in Rule 3.2, a "Starter" is defined as one of the five players established in the Team's starting lineup for any given game.

This part is fairly straightforward - we don’t want teams undermining the goal of this policy by keeping Residents on the bench while they play majority non-exempt non-Resident starting lineups. This rule ensures that the team actually playing is able to maintain a good balance of local and foreign talent.

f) World Championship Event. The World Championship Event is intended to bring together the best teams from each region to compete, as representatives of their region, in a global competition. In order to foster this diverse global competition, nurture regional teams, excite local and global fans, increase participation from all regions, and ensure a fair and open championship, all teams competing in the World Championship Event must meet local residency requirements. At least 60% (three out of five) Starters on any competing team must be Residents or exempt non-Residents of the region they represent in the World Championship Event. This Rule shall ensure that the goals of the World Championship Event are achieved, without undue burden on players and teams, while promoting fair play and robust competition for all participants in this global competition.

g) NA and EU LCS. The NA and EU LCS, including the NA and EU regular season and all matches leading up to the regional playoffs, are designed to identify the teams that will represent the NA and EU in the World Championship Event. In order to fulfill this mandate, all teams competing in the LCS and LCS-affiliated matches must meet the requirements in Rule 1.2(f) for teams participating in the World Championship Event, including the requirement that at least 60% (three out of five) Starters on each team be Residents of the region covered by the LCS in which they play.

h) NA and EU Challenger Series. The NA and EU Challenger Series, including the NA and EU Challenger Series regular season and all matches leading up to the Promotion Tournament, are designed to identify the teams from the NA and EU that will be promoted to the NA and EU LCS and thereby have an opportunity to represent the NA and EU in the World Championship Event. In order to fulfill this mandate, all teams competing in the Challenger Series and Challenger Series-affiliated matches must meet the requirements in Rule 1.2(f) for teams participating in the World Championship Event, including the requirement that at least 60% (three out of five) Starters on each team be Residents of the region covered by the Challenger Series in which they play.

This is the heart of the rule - having at least 3 players on every team be local to that region in some sense ensures that regional identity is preserved for a league. That principle should be reflected at every level of professional competition, from the Challenger Series all the way to representation at Worlds. Keep in mind that this specific version of the residency requirement is only going into the LCS ruleset, so it will only apply to LCS teams attending Worlds, not all Worlds-participating teams.

i) Implementation of Rule Change; Grandfathering. Any player on the Active Roster of an LCS team or a CS team who participated in the most recent Promotion Tournament at the time of this policy change who would not satisfy the Resident definition in 1.2(a) will be considered an "exempt non-resident", which allows such a player to count towards the three Residents required pursuant to Rules 1.2(f), 1.2(g), and 1.2(h). Once an exempt non-resident has met the Residency requirement, that player will be considered a Resident. A player cannot simultaneously count as a Resident for one region and as an exempt non-Resident for another region. A player can choose to waive his exempt non-Resident status in favor of counting as a Resident for another region before December 31, 11:59 pm PST 2014. In the event that a team has two or more exempt non-Resident players as Starters, they will not be permitted to add any additional non-exempt non-Residents as Starters.

This rule ensures that current LCS teams and CS teams who played in the Promotion Tournament do not have to change their rosters. In enacting the Interregional Movement Policy, it’s important to us that players already committed to playing in the region are not unduly harmed. At the same time, in the long term it’s important that changes to teams gradually move each team to a healthy balance of foreign and local talent, which is why we make the subtle distinction between Resident players and exempt non-Resident players. Allowing players to waive an exemption means that individuals who aren’t sure of the plans don’t get locked out of legitimate options. Players currently in NA can choose to waive their exemption if they would qualify as an EU resident, and vice-versa.

j) Substitutes: All teams will be required to maintain at least one Resident player as a substitute at any given time. At no point in time will teams be permitted to make a substitution which is in violation of any provision of this Rule 1.2.:

If for some reason a Starter is temporarily out of commission, we don’t want teams put in a position where they can’t field a roster in compliance with the Interregional Movement Policy. That’s why we’re requiring teams keep at least one Resident substitute on the roster as a failsafe.

k) Losing Residency: For purposes of this Rule 1.2, a player who is considered a Resident for a region will no longer be deemed to be a "Resident" of that region if such player has been primarily present in another region for 24 out of the last 36 months.

In the event that a player wants to take a break from competitive play, or has a short stint in another league that doesn’t work out, we want to make sure that they reserve the option of playing in the region where they were most recently a Resident. Giving the players the safety net of temporarily exploring options overseas without forfeiting Resident status is a priority for us, and that’s what this portion of the rule is meant to address. So, for example, an EU Resident player can join an NA team for a year, and if circumstances change and they want to go back to EU, they can do so without having lost their EU Resident status.

l) Work Eligibility: Each player must submit proof that, at the time of any LCS-affiliated match the player wishes to participate in, he/she will be (a) a legal resident of a country in their region, and (b) work-eligible in the United States (for NA players) or Germany (for EU players).

This is the same as the old residency rule: because portions of the Challenger Series and all of the LCS occur live and at a physical location, it’s important that players are present and eligible to work in the country where the event is being held.

The Interregional Movement Policy is one that benefits the overall competitive ecosystem, and other regional leagues will be incorporating something similar to the NA and EU version of the Regional Residency Requirement & Work Eligibility and releasing their equivalents at their discretion. China (LPL & LSPL), Korea (OGN The Champions, Masters & NLB), and Southeast Asia/Taiwan (GPL & LNL) handling their regional residency requirements individually. The NA and EU requirement provides a robust framework that will not only preserve regional identity in the future, but permit a healthy amount of movement between regions that is to the benefit of esports as a whole.

유럽 LCS 소개

리그 오브 레전드 챔피언십 시리즈(LCS)는 북미와 유럽의 최상위 리그 오브 레전드 e스포츠 리그입니다. 북미와 유럽 각각의 LCS는 10개 팀으로 구성되며 2라운드 풀리그로 한 시즌에 총 18경기를 진행합니다. 경기는 단판제로 실시되며 각 팀은 하루에 한 번씩 경기합니다. 한 시즌은 스프링과 서머, 두 스플릿으로 나뉩니다.

순위 결정전:

  • 두 팀의 기록이 같을 때 상대 전적으로 순위를 결정합니다.
  • 그래도 순위를 결정할 수 없는 경우, 순위 결정전을 실시합니다.

플레이오프 형식:

LCS 플레이오프는 시드 배정을 받은 6팀으로 구성되며 토너먼트로 진행됩니다. 모든 경기는 5전3선승제이며 3/4위전도 실시합니다.

챔피언십 포인트

2015 LCS 시즌부터 북미와 유럽 리그는 챔피언십 포인트 제도(서킷 포인트로도 알려짐)를 채택해 월드 챔피언십 출전팀을 결정합니다. 챔피언십 포인트 제도는 참가팀이 항상 최상의 기량을 뽐내고 다른 지역 리그와 발맞추어 나갈 수 있도록 도입됩니다.

LCS 팀의 월드 챔피언십 진출 자격 요건:

  • 서머 스플릿의 1위 팀은 월드 챔피언십 자동진출권(AQ)을 얻으며 지역 1번 시드를 배정받습니다.
  • 한 시즌 챔피언 포인트 누적 합산 1위 팀도 월드 챔피언십 출전권을 얻으며 2번 시드를 배정받습니다.
  • 서머 스플릿 종료 시 여러 팀이 동점이면 서머 스플릿에서 획득한 포인트가 가장 많은 팀에게 출전권이 주어집니다.
  • 지역 3번 시드는 북미와 유럽 지역 예선의 각 우승팀에게 배정됩니다.

챔피언십 포인트 규정:

순위 스프링 서머
1위 90 AQ
2위 70 90
3위 50 70
4위 30 40
5~6위 10 20
7위 0 0

 

관전 방법

매주 캘리포니아 산타모니카의 북미 LCS 스튜디오나 독일 베를린 유럽 LCS 스튜디오에서 직접 경기를 관람하실 수 있습니다.

---- LCS 규정

LCS 규정

LCS 규정 – 서론 및 목적

리그 오브 레전드 챔피언십 시리즈(“LCS”)의 본 공식 규정(“규정”)은 2015년 LCS 참가 자격이 주어진 모든 팀과 그 감독, 코치, 선수, 기타 직원에게 적용됩니다. LCS 시즌3은 두 기간(“스플릿”)으로 나누어 진행됩니다. 각 스플릿은 (a) 정규 시즌, (b) 정규 시즌 종료 시 시작되는 플레이오프, (c) 플레이오프 후 진행되는 승강전의 3단계로 구성됩니다. 북미 LCS와 유럽 LCS, 그리고 전 세계 기타 지역의 상위 팀은 시즌3 리그 오브 레전드 월드 챔피언십에 진출합니다. 본 규정은 공식 LCS 경기에만 적용되며 리그 오브 레전드(“LoL” 또는 “게임”)의 기타 대회, 토너먼트, 또는 조직된 경기에는 적용되지 않습니다.

델라웨어 주 유한 책임 회사인 League of Legends Championship Series LLC는 LCS 프로 경기에서 사용되는 규정을 통일하고 표준화하고자 LoL 프로 경기의 본 규정을 수립하였습니다.

본 규정은 LCS가 LoL 프로 경기용으로 구축한 시스템의 무결성 및 프로 수준에서 경기하는 팀 간의 경쟁적 균형을 보장하고자 하는 목적으로만 수립되었습니다. 규정 표준화는 팀과 선수, 총감독을 비롯해 LoL 프로 경기에 참여하는 모든 당사자의 이익을 위한 것입니다.

본 규정은 선수 경쟁을 제한하지 않습니다. 선수와 팀 간의 계약은 각 팀과 소속 선수의 재량에 따르며 팀과 각 선수의 서면 계약서에 명시합니다.

LCS 규정 전문은 여기에서 다운로드할 수 있습니다.

변경 및 업데이트 내역은 변경내역에서 확인하시기 바랍니다.

---- 글로벌 규정

글로벌 규정

글로벌 계약 현황 데이터베이스는 여기에서 다운로드하실 수 있습니다.

지역 간 탬퍼링 금지 정책

 

지역 간 탬퍼링 금지 정책이란 무엇인가요?

프로팀 소속 선수 및 관계자는 각 지역 최상위 리그 팀 소속으로 리그에서 공인한 계약 관계에 있는 선수를 영입하기 위해 선수에게 권유, 유도, 또는 논의를 할 수 없습니다. 마찬가지로, 리그에서 공인한 계약 관계에 있는 선수들 또한 다른 팀의 선수 및 관계자에게 권유 및 접촉하는 것이 금지됩니다. 만약 양 팀의 승인을 얻지 않은 채로 지속적인 영입 논의가 진행될 경우, 탬퍼링을 시도한 쪽과 탬퍼링 대상 선수 양쪽 모두가 리그 운영진의 재량에 따라 제재를 받게 됩니다.

리그에서 공인한 계약 관계에 있는 선수를 영입하고자 하는 팀은 가장 먼저 해당 선수와의 계약 당사자인 해당 팀 사무국과 접촉해야 합니다.

양 팀은 이적에 대해 서로 합의한 후, 영입하려는 팀과 영입 대상 선수가 접촉하기 전에 각 팀의 소속 지역 라이엇 게임즈 사무소에 해당 합의 사항에 대해 알려야 하며, 이때 양 팀 사무국의 확인서를 이메일로 송부해야 합니다.

리그에 새로 참가하려는 팀 및 해당 팀 관계자 또한 선수에게 탬퍼링을 시도할 경우 마찬가지로 제재 대상이 되며, 라이엇 공인 리그 및 대회에 대한 참가를 금지하는 등의 제재가 부과될 수도 있습니다.

선수를 영입하고 싶을 때, 해당 선수가 계약 중인지 아닌지 어떻게 알 수 있나요?

각 팀은 어떤 선수가 영입 가능한 상태인지 문의할 수 있습니다. 다만, 선수가 계약 상태인 경우 해당 팀의 사무국에 문의해야 합니다.

상기 링크의 데이터베이스에는 각 지역 리그에서 공인한 계약(최저 연봉 등 최소한의 리그 기준을 만족하는 계약)을 맺고 리그에 참가 중인 선수들의 계약 만료 일자가 담겨 있습니다. 또한 계약을 맺은 팀에서 동의한 경우 해당 팀의 연락처 또한 포함되어 있습니다. 이 데이터베이스는 매 스플릿 개막 시에 갱신되며 또한, 팀 로스터 변동을 반영하기 위해 주기적으로 갱신됩니다.

이 데이터베이스는 여러 팀과 선수들 간의 공정한 소통 과정을 돕기 위한 것입니다. 데이터베이스에 올라있지 않은 선수라도 리그에서 공인하는 계약 관계에 있다고 봐야 할 합리적인 이유가 있을 경우(예: 리그 공인 계약을 맺고 리그에 등장한 신인 선수로 정보가 아직 데이터베이스에 등록되지 않은 경우 등)에는 해당 선수와 직접 접촉해선 안 되며 소속팀 사무국과 접촉해야 합니다.

선수로서 소속팀을 떠나고 싶으면, 어떻게 할 수 있나요?

계약 관계에 있는 선수들은 다른 팀 관계자와 직접 접촉할 수 없지만, 아래와 같은 선택을 할 수 있습니다.

  • 팀을 떠나고 싶다는 의사를 공개적으로 밝히고, 영입에 관심 있는 관계자들은 현 소속팀 사무국에 연락해 달라고 밝힙니다
  • 이때, 선수는 공개적으로든 개인적으로든 특정 팀을 지칭하여 현 소속팀 사무국에 접촉해 달라고 할 수 없습니다.
  • 계약상에 바이아웃(buyout)* 조항이 있을 경우 이를 행사하여 팀을 떠날 수 있습니다.
  • 계약이 만료된 후 다른 팀들과 접촉합니다 (일반적으로 오프시즌이 이 시기가 됩니다).

구체적으로 제한되는 내용은 아래와 같습니다.

  • 각 팀 및 팀 관계자는 계약 중인 선수와 향후의 영입 가능성에 대해 직접 논의할 수 없습니다.
  • 각 팀은 계약 중인 선수를 영입하려 할 경우 해당 선수의 소속팀과 직접 논의해야 합니다.
  • 팀 소속으로 계약 중인 선수는 직접 다른 팀과 영입 논의를 할 수 없습니다.
  • 계약 상태가 아닌 선수는 자신을 영입할 만한 팀과 직접 논의할 수 있으며, 반대의 경우도 마찬가지로 가능합니다.

이러한 탬퍼링 금지 정책을 적용하는 이유는 무엇인가요?

탬퍼링 금지는 조직의 안정성을 보장하고 대회 부정 시비를 피하기 위해 필요합니다. 선수들이 시즌 도중에 경쟁 팀으로부터 영입 제안을 받아 최상의 실력을 발휘하지 않을 유혹을 느끼거나, 경기 준비에 소홀해지지 않도록 하는 것은 매우 중요합니다.

선수와 팀 사이의 계약이란, 선수가 계약 기간 동안 팀을 위해 플레이하고 이에 대한 정당한 대가를 받겠다고 합의한 것입니다. 선수가 시즌 도중에 다른 팀의 영입 제안으로 인해 갑작스럽게 계약을 해지하게 되면 팀과 선수에게 모두 혼란스러운 환경이 조성되며, 리그의 안정성을 크게 해치게 됩니다.

그렇다고 선수가 팀을 옮기거나 자신에게 가장 잘 맞는 팀을 찾는 것 자체를 방지하고자 하는 것은 아닙니다. 소속 팀의 사무국과 이적 논의를 진행할 수도 있고, 아예 계약 기간이 만료된 후에 원하는 다른 팀과 협의할 수도 있습니다. 또한 계약에 바이아웃 조항이 있다면 직접 행사할 수도 있습니다. 궁극적으로 계약은 선수와 팀 양쪽 모두의 이익을 위한 것입니다. 선수는 계약을 통해 소속 및 보수의 안정성을 얻을 수 있습니다. 팀 입장에서 계약은 선수가 팀을 위해 플레이할 것이며 팀을 떠나려 할 때는 소속팀이 논의에서 소외되지 않을 것이라는 보장입니다. 이러한 관계를 보호하는 것은 매우 중요하며, 탬퍼링 방지는 이를 위한 수단 중 하나입니다.

지역 간 이적 정책

1.2 지역 내 거주자 지위 및 노동허가

a) 거주자의 정의. 본 1.2항의 목적상, 지역에서 합법적으로 거주해 왔으며 규정이 적용되는 대회의 첫 경기(즉, 월드 챔피언십, LCS, 챌린저 시리즈의 경기)에 참가하기 직전 36개월 중 24개월 이상을 해당 지역 내에 주로 거주한 선수를 “거주자”로 정의합니다. 거주자의 정의를 시민권이나 법률문서가 아닌 지역 내에서의 지속적인 장기간의 거주를 기준으로 내리는 정책을 도입합니다. 본 정책은 참가하고자 하는 리그의 지역에 장기적으로 거주하고 있는 자를 거주자로 정의하는 동시에, 한 리그에서 장기간 활동한 선수라면 누구나 해당 지역의 거주자가 될 수 있는 권리를 보장합니다. 자격을 논할 때, 합리적인 수준의 재량에 따라 휴가 및 기타 일시적인 이동을 허용할 수 있도록 “주로 거주”라는 표현을 사용합니다.

b) 거주 증명. 모든 선수는 월드 챔피언십, 북미 및 유럽 LCS, 북미 및 유럽 챌린저 시리즈에 참가할 시 자격 요건 양식을 제출하고 1.2(c)호 및 1.2(d)호의 정의에 따라 거주 증빙 자료를 제시해 거주 사실을 증명해야 합니다. 팀은 소속 선수가 1.2항의 거주 요건을 충족할 수 있도록 해야 합니다. 선수(또는 선수의 부모나 법적 보호자)가 허위이거나 오해의 소지가 있거나 불완전한 정보를 제공해 이 선수의 거주자 지위 및 지역이 잘못 분류된 경우에는 소속팀과 선수 모두 본 규정을 위반한 것으로 처리됩니다. 팀이나 선수가 1.2항을 위반하면 10.2항의 위반으로 간주하며 10.5항 및 10.6항의 제재를 부과합니다.

c) 거주 증빙 자료. 만 18세 이상인 선수는 모두 활동하려는 지역에서의 실질적 거주 사실을 입증하는 증빙 서류를 제출해 거주지를 증명합니다. 증빙 서류 형식의 예는 다음과 같습니다.

  • 정부 발급 서류. 운전면허증, 선거인 등록증, 차량 등록증, 정부 복지 서비스 급여증, 군대 또는 징병 등록부 등, 거주지를 증명하는 정부 발행 기록이나 증명의 사본을 제출해 거주 사실을 입증할 수 있습니다.
  • 민간 발급 서류. 학교기록, 권리증서, 임대차 계약서, 주택 소유주 협회 증빙, 공공요금 고지서(실제 거주 수준의 사용량이 기록된 가스, 수도, 전기, 케이블, 전화 등의 고지서), 은행 기록 및 입출금 내역서, 소득세 신고서, 보험 증빙, 의료 기록 및 고용 기록의 사본을 제출해 거주 사실을 입증할 수 있습니다.

d) 미성년자의 거주 사실. 만 18세 미만인 선수는 다음 둘 중 하나로 거주 사실을 입증합니다.

  • 학교 기록. 해당 지역의 전일제 학교 출석 증빙으로 거주 사실을 입증할 수 있습니다. 증빙에는 학교 관계자의 인증을 받은 성적표, 등록 증명, 출석부의 사본 등이 있습니다.
  • 부모의 기록. (i) 부모의 성명이 적힌 출생증명서 등, 부모자녀 관계를 입증할 수 있는 서류 및 (ii) 1.2(c)호에 규정된 거주지 증빙 서류 요건에 맞춘, 부모 중 한 사람의 해당 지역 내 거주 사실 증빙을 제출해 거주 사실을 입증할 수 있습니다.

최근 3년 중 2년을 지역 내에서 거주했다는 사실을 증명하는 절차가 다소 까다로우므로 도움이 되고자 증빙의 범주를 지정했습니다. 결국에는 적절한 판단을 기초로 거주지 판정이 이루어지지만, 선수의 기회를 제한하지 않도록 다양한 종류의 증빙을 허용합니다. 또한 로스터 변경 시 충분히 검토할 시간을 주기 위해 변경 신청 서류 제출 기한을 늘릴 것이며 각 경우에 적합한 서류를 받을 수 있도록 팀과 협력할 것입니다.

e) 선발 선수. 1.2항의 목적상, 3.2항에 명시된 대로 한 경기에서 팀의 선발명단에 오른 다섯 선수를 “선발 선수”로 정의합니다.

프로 팀이 거주자 선수는 후보로 두고 선발명단의 대부분은 예외 적용을 받지 않는 비거주자로 구성하게 되면 정책의 목표에 부합하지 않으므로 다음 규정을 시행합니다. 실제 경기에 참여하는 선수단 내에서 현지 선수와 외국인 선수의 균형을 적절히 유지하기 위해 필요한 규정입니다.

f) 월드 챔피언십. 월드 챔피언십은 각 지역 최고의 팀이 지역을 대표해 국제 대회에서 서로 경쟁할 수 있는 장을 마련하고자 실시됩니다. 월드 챔피언십의 다양성 증대, 지역팀 육성, 현지 및 전 세계 팬의 열기 고취, 전 지역의 참여도 향상, 공정하고 개방적인 대회 보장을 위해 월드 챔피언십에 참여하는 모든 팀은 현지 거주요건을 충족해야 합니다. 어떤 출전팀이든 선발 선수의 60%(다섯 명 중 세 명) 이상은 월드 챔피언십 참가 시 대표하는 지역의 거주자이거나 예외 비거주자여야 합니다. 이 규정은 선수와 팀에 과도한 부담을 주지 않으면서 월드 챔피언십의 목표를 달성하고 이 국제무대에서 모든 출전팀이 공정하고 건전한 경기를 치를 수 있도록 세워졌습니다.

g) 북미 및 유럽 LCS. 북미 및 유럽 정규 시즌과 지역 플레이오프에 이르는 모든 경기를 포함하는 북미 및 유럽 LCS는 월드 챔피언십에서 북미와 유럽을 대표할 팀을 선정하는 대회입니다. 이 목적에 맞게 LCS 경기 및 LCS 관련 경기에 임하는 모든 팀은 1.2(f)호의 월드 챔피언십 참가팀 요건을 충족해야 합니다. 이에 따라 각 팀 선발 선수의 60%(다섯 명 중 세 명) 이상은 활동하는 LCS 지역의 거주자여야 합니다.

h) 북미 및 유럽 챌린저 시리즈. 북미 및 유럽 챌린저 시리즈 정규 시즌과 승강전에 이르는 모든 경기를 포함하는 북미 및 유럽 챌린저 시리즈는 북미와 유럽 지역에서 해당 LCS로 승격되어 월드 챔피언십에서 해당 지역을 대표할 기회를 얻을 팀을 선별하는 대회입니다. 이 목적에 맞게 챌린저 시리즈 경기와 챌린저 시리즈 관련 경기에 임하는 모든 팀은 1.2(f)호의 월드 챔피언십 참가팀 요건을 충족해야 합니다. 이에 따라 각 팀 선발 선수의 60%(다섯 명 중 세 명) 이상은 활동하는 챌린저 시리즈 지역의 거주자여야 합니다.

팀마다 적어도 세 명은 대표하는 지역의 현지인이라 할 수 있다면 리그의 지역적 정체성을 유지할 수 있다는 게 이 규정의 골자입니다. 이 원칙은 챌린저 시리즈부터 월드 챔피언십에 이르기까지 모든 수준의 프로 대회에서 따라야 합니다. 이 규정에 명시된 거주요건은 LCS 규정집에만 포함되므로 월드 챔피언십에 출전하는 모든 팀이 아니라 월드 챔피언십에 출전하는 LCS 팀에만 적용된다는 사실에 주의하시기 바랍니다.

i) 규정 변경 시 예외 적용. 본 정책이 변경될 당시의 LCS팀 현역 선수나 직전의 승강전에 출전했던 챌린저 시리즈 팀의 현역 선수 중에서 1.2(a)호의 정의에 따라 거주자가 아닌 것으로 분류되는 선수는 “예외 비거주자”로 간주하며 1.2(f), 1.2(g), 1.2(h)호의 거주자 세 명을 집계할 때 포함할 수 있습니다. 예외 비거주자가 거주자 요건을 충족하게 되면 거주자로 간주합니다. 한 선수를 동시에 한 지역의 거주자이자 다른 지역의 예외 비거주자로 산정할 수 없습니다. 이 경우 다른 지역의 거주자로 등록하려면 태평양 표준시 기준 2014년 12월 31일 오후 11시 59분 이전에 예외 비거주자 지위를 포기할 수 있습니다. 한 팀에 예외 비거주자 선발 선수가 두 명 이상이면 예외 적용을 받지 않는 비거주자를 선발 선수로 더 추가할 수 없습니다.

이 규정은 현 LCS팀과 승강전에 출전했던 CS팀이 선수단을 변경할 필요가 없도록 세워졌습니다. 한 지역에 이미 전념하고 있는 선수가 지역 간 이적 정책을 수립하는 과정에서 지나치게 피해를 입어서는 안 되기 때문이며, 장기적으로 모든 팀이 외국인 선수와 현지인 선수의 균형을 적절히 유지하는 방향으로 가는 것도 중요하기 때문에 거주자 선수와 예외 비거주자 선수의 구분을 두었습니다. 그리고 선수의 예외 지위 포기를 허용해 정당한 선택권을 잃지 않도록 합니다. 현재 북미에서 활동하고 있지만 유럽 거주자 조건에 부합하는 경우 예외 지위를 포기할 수 있으며 유럽에서 활동하는 북미 거주자의 경우에도 가능합니다.

j) 후보 선수: 모든 팀은 적어도 한 명의 거주자 후보 선수를 상시 두어야 합니다. 어떠한 때라도 선수를 교체하면서 1.2항에 포함된 조항을 어겨서는 안 됩니다.

어떠한 연유로 선발 선수가 경기에 일시적으로 참가하지 못하는 상황에서 지역 간 이적 정책을 준수하느라 교체 선수를 마련하지 못하는 일이 생기지 않도록, 후보 선수 중 적어도 한 명은 거주자여야 합니다.

k) 거주자 지위 상실. 본 규정 1.2호의 목적상, 한 지역의 거주자로 간주되는 선수가 다른 지역에서 최근 36개월 중 24개월을 주로 거주한 경우, 이 선수는 앞선 지역의 “거주자” 지위를 잃은 것으로 간주합니다.

선수가 프로 활동을 잠시 쉬거나 다른 리그에서 잠깐 활약했다가 돌아오는 경우, 가장 최근에 거주자였던 지역에서 다시 활동할 수 있는 권리를 보호하고자 합니다. 선수가 거주자 지위를 유지하면서 잠시 다른 지역에서 가능성을 찾아 나설 수 있는 안전망을 갖는 건 매우 중요하며 이를 보장하기 위해 이 조항을 도입했습니다. 예를 들어, 유럽 거주자인 선수가 1년 동안 북미팀에서 활동하다가 상황이 바뀌어 유럽으로 돌아가고자 하는 경우 가지고 있던 유럽 거주자 지위를 잃지 않고 되돌아갈 수 있습니다.

l) 노동허가. 모든 선수는 참가를 원하는 모든 LCS 관련 경기가 실시될 때 (a) 해당 지역 내 국가의 합법적 거주자이며 (b) (북미 선수의 경우)미국 또는 (유럽 선수의 경우)독일에서 일할 수 있는 허가를 받았음을 입증하는 증빙을 제출해야 합니다.

이 조항은 예전 거주요건 규정과 동일합니다. 챌린저 시리즈의 일부 경기와 LCS의 모든 경기가 정해진 장소에서 실시간으로 진행되므로 선수는 대회 개최국에 있어야 하며 그 국가의 노동허가를 보유하고 있어야 합니다.

지역 간 이적 정책은 프로 리그에 관여하는 모두에게 유익한 정책으로, 다른 지역 리그도 북미, 유럽의 지역 내 거주자 지위 및 노동허가 규정과 유사한 규정을 도입해 재량에 따라 공개할 예정입니다. 중국(LPL 및 LSPL), 한국(온게임넷 챔피언스, 마스터즈, NLB), 동남아/대만(GPL 및 LNL)은 개별적으로 지역 내 거주자 지위 규정을 관리합니다. 북미 및 유럽의 규정은 향후 지역의 정체성을 유지하는 동시에 건전한 수준의 지역 간 이동을 허용해 궁극적으로는 e스포츠계 전체에 혜택을 가져다주는 탄탄한 틀의 역할을 합니다.

글로벌 페널티 인덱스

ABOUT EU LCS

ABOUT EU LCS

The League of Legends Championship Series (LCS) is the preeminent League of Legends esports league in North America and Europe. Each LCS league (NA and EU) is comprised of 10 teams facing every other team twice over the course of the season, for a total of 18 matches each. The competition stretches across two splits, Spring and Summer. For the spring split, matches are played in a Best of 1 format. For the summer split, matches will be played in a Best of 2 format. Read about the format changes here.

Teams playing in the Bo2 format are awarded points depending on the result of each Bo2:

  • Win - 3 points
  • Draw - 1 point
  • Loss - 0 points

Tiebreakers:

  • If two or more teams hold the same point record, the standing will be decided by amount of matches won
  • If the teams have the same amount of matches won, ties will be broken by Head to Head record
  • If two or more teams hold the same Head to Head record, the winning percentage based on total games played will be used
  • If still tied, tiebreaker matches will be played to determine final standings

Playoff Format:

LCS playoffs are comprised of six teams in a seeded, single elimination tournament. All matches are Best of 5 format. A third/fourth place match is played.

Championship points

Starting with the 2015 LCS season, NA and EU leagues will utilize Championship Points (otherwise known to some as circuit points) for World Championship qualification. The Championship Point system ensures that teams always play their best and allows for better alignment with other international leagues.

Here’s how an LCS team qualifies for Worlds:

  • 1st place team of the Summer Split will automatically qualify (AQ) for Worlds as the first seed from that region.
  • The team that has accrued the most championship points throughout the season will also qualify for Worlds as the second seed.
  • In the event that multiple teams are tied in the standings at the conclusion of the Summer Split, then the team that gained the most points in the Summer Split will be considered the holder of the tiebreaker.
  • The final spot for Worlds will be determined at the NA and EU Regional Qualifiers, the winners of which will be the third seeds of their respective regions.

Points will be awarded in the following way:

Place Spring Split Summer Split
1st 90 AQ
2nd 70 90
3rd 50 70
4th 30 40
5th-6th 10 20
7th-10th 0 0

 

How to watch

You can attend matches live every week at the NA LCS studio in Santa Monica, CA, or the EU LCS studio in Berlin, Germany. Click on the "Tickets" tab for more information on seeing the LCS in person. You can also watch the LCS live every week on lolesports or on our spoiler-free vods page once the match is finished.

---- RULES

RULES

LCS RULES - INTRODUCTION AND PURPOSE

These Official Rules (“Rules”) of the League of Legends Championship Series (“LCS”) apply to each of the teams who have qualified to play in the LCS in 2015, as well as their managers, coaches, players, and other employees. Season Three of the LCS will be divided into two halves (“splits”). Each split will consist of three phases (a) a regular season, (b) playoffs, which will be at the conclusion of the regular season, and (c) a promotion/relegation tournament after the playoffs are conducted. The top teams from the LCS division in North America, the LCS division in Europe, and from other regions around the world will advance to the Season Three League of Legends World Championship. These Rules apply only to official LCS play and not to other competitions, tournaments or organized play of League of Legends (“LoL” or the “game”).

League of Legends Championship Series LLC, a Delaware limited liability company, has established these Rules for the competitive play of LoL in order to unify and standardize the rules used in LCS competitive play.

These Rules are designed solely to ensure the integrity of the system established by the LCS for professional play of LoL and a competitive balance among the teams that play at the professional level. Standardized rules benefit all parties who are involved in the professional play of LoL, including the teams, players and general managers.

These Rules do not restrict competition for players. The terms of engagement between players and teams are left to each of the teams and its players and are set forth in written agreements between a team and each of its players (“Player Agreement”).

The complete LCS Rules document can be downloaded here.

For a breakdown of changes and updates, visit our changelog.

LCS PENALTY INDEX

Click here to view the LCS Penalty Index. For more information on the index, please view our article breakdown here.

---- GLOBAL RULES

GLOBAL RULES

The Global Contract Database can be viewed here.

The Global Suspension Database can be viewed here.

INTERREGIONAL ANTI-POACHING AND ANTI-TAMPERING POLICY

 

What is the interregional anti-poaching and anti-tampering policy?

No team member or affiliate of a team may engage in the solicitation, luring, or discussion of employment of a player who is under a league-recognized contract with a professional team competing in the top-level league of a region. Similarly, players under league-recognized contracts cannot solicit or reach out directly to other team members or affiliates of other teams. In the event of prolonged discussions of employment that aren't sanctioned by the management of both teams, both the party attempting to poach and the player being poached will be subject to penalties at the discretion of league officials.

Should any interested team wish to engage in conversation with a player under a league-recognized contract with another team, they must first contact the management of the team holding the contract.

League Notification: 

After the teams have come to an agreement and before initiating contact between the interested team and player of interest, they must notify their respective regional office of the agreement, with confirmation from both teams' management via email.

Prospective teams and team affiliates (owners seeking to enter a league, etc.) attempting to poach players will also be subject to sanctions, up to and including denial of entry into Riot-sanctioned leagues and competitive events.

If I'm interested in acquiring a player, how do I know if he or she is currently under contract?

As a team, you can inquire about the availability of players - it just needs to be to the player's management so long as that player is under contract.

The database linked above contains the contract end-dates of contracted players currently participating in leagues where there are league-recognized contracts (i.e., contracts that conform with league minimum standards, such as minimum player compensation). It also includes contact information for teams who have volunteered contact information. It will be updated at the beginning of every split and periodically during the split to reflect roster modifications.

This database is intended as a resource to facilitate legitimate communication between teams and players. Where there is good reason to believe a player is under a league-recognized contract despite not being in the database (e.g. a brand new player in a league with officially-recognized contracts not yet having his or her information reflected in the database), teams are expected to contact management rather than approach players directly.

If I'm a contracted player interested in leaving my team, what are my options?

While contracted players cannot reach out to other teams' affiliates, they can:

  • Publicly state their interest in leaving their team and encourage any and all interested party to contact their management.
  • Players cannot encourage specific teams, publicly or privately, to reach out to their management.
  • Exercise a buyout clause in their contract to leave their team if one exists.
  • Reach out to teams once their contract expires (typically during the off-season for most players).

Clarification of restrictions:

  • Teams and affiliates of those teams cannot engage in discussions with players under contract regarding potential employment.
  • Teams are to reach out to other teams directly regarding employment of contracted players.
  • Players under contract with a team should not engage in employment discussion directly with other teams.
  • Players not under contract are free to reach out to potential employers and vice-versa.

Why do you have the current poaching policy?

Poaching protections are important both for the stability of organizations and to avoid competitive integrity issues. During the season, it's important that players aren't being distracted from their preparation or being tempted to play at less than 100% by offers of employment from rival teams.

When players and teams sign a contract they are entering into an agreement that a player will play for a team during a defined period of time and be duly compensated for their play - players abruptly dissolving their contracts due to employment discussions with other teams during the season creates a chaotic environment for teams and players and undermines the stability of the competitive ecosystem.

This doesn't mean that we want to prevent players from ever switching teams or finding the team that is the best fit for them - discussing the possibility of being traded to another team with their management, or simply waiting until their current contract is up before engaging in any negotiation they want. For players whose contract includes a buyout clause, that's an option they may be able to exercise as well. Ultimately, the value of contracts goes both ways. For players, contracts provide stability and the promise of a paycheck. For teams, contracts guarantee that contracted players play for their team and if a player wants to leave a team, the team management are a necessary part of that discussion. This is an important dynamic to preserve, and poaching protections are one way of doing so.

INTERREGIONAL MOVEMENT POLICY

1.2 REGIONAL RESIDENCY REQUIREMENT & WORK ELIGIBILITY

a) Resident Defined. For purposes of this Rule 1.2, a player is deemed to be a "Resident" of a region if such player has legally resided and been primarily present in such region for no less than twenty-four months out of the thirty-six months immediately prior to such players' participation in the first game of the applicable tournament (i.e., a match in the World Championship Event, LCS, or Challenger Series).

In defining a Resident, we sought to create a policy that defines Residents based on sustained and prolonged presence with a region, rather than citizenship or legal documentation. This policy makes sure that Residents not only have resided in the region whose league they wish to play in for a substantial period of time, it also gives every player the option of becoming a Resident for that league after a prolonged commitment. We used the language “primarily present” so that a reasonable amount of discretion can be used in allowing for vacations and other such temporary travel when considering eligibility.

b) Certification of Residency. All players shall certify their residency upon participation in the World Championship Event, the NA and EU LCS, and the NA and EU Challenger Series by submitting an eligibility form, and providing proof of residency as defined in Rules 1.2(c) and (d). Each team is responsible for ensuring that its players meet the residency requirements in this Rule 1.2. It shall be a violation of these Rules, by both the team and the player, if a player (or his or her parent or guardian) provides false, misleading or incomplete information resulting in the misclassification of such player’s residency and region. A violation of this Rule 1.2 by a team or a player shall also be deemed a violation of Rule 10.2, and the disciplinary measures in Rules 10.5 and 10.6 shall apply.

c) Proof of Residency. Any player over eighteen years of age may prove residency by the provision of documentary evidence sufficient to demonstrate actual residence in the region in which he or she wishes to play. Such documentary evidence may be in the form of one or more examples of:

  • i. Government Issued Documentation. A player may prove residency by providing copies of a driver’s license, voter registration form, vehicle registration, government benefits records, military or draft registration papers or other government-issued records or identification that demonstrate residency.
  • ii. Private Documentation. A player may prove residency by providing copies of school records, deeds, leases, homeowners association documents, utility bills (such as gas, water, electricity, cable, or telephone, provided that all show levels of use consistent with actual residency), bank records and statements, tax returns, insurance documents, medical records and employment records.
    •

d) Residency of Minors. Players who are below eighteen years of age may prove residency by either:

  • i. School Records. A player may prove residency by providing proof of full-time attendance at school in the region, including by providing copies of report cards, enrollment documentation, or attendance records certified by school officials; or
  • ii. Parents’ Records. A player may prove residency by (i) providing documentary evidence of the parent-child relationship, such as a birth certificate that lists the names of parents, and (ii) proof that one parent lives in the region, which may be demonstrated by provision of documentary evidence sufficient to prove residency as specified in Rule 1.2(c), above.
    •

Proving that a player has resided in a region for two out of the last three years can be a somewhat tricky process, so we’ve given categories of documentation that can help establish a player’s Resident status. This is ultimately a process that relies on making good judgment calls, but by permitting numerous categories of proof we can ensure that no player is left without options. We’ll be increasing the timeframe during which a team should submit its paperwork to register a roster change to make sure each change can be assessed within a reasonable period of time, and working with teams to collect paperwork that is acceptable for each circumstance.

e) Starters. For purposes of Rule 1.2, as stated in Rule 3.2, a "Starter" is defined as one of the five players established in the Team's starting lineup for any given game.

This part is fairly straightforward - we don’t want teams undermining the goal of this policy by keeping Residents on the bench while they play majority non-exempt non-Resident starting lineups. This rule ensures that the team actually playing is able to maintain a good balance of local and foreign talent.

f) World Championship Event. The World Championship Event is intended to bring together the best teams from each region to compete, as representatives of their region, in a global competition. In order to foster this diverse global competition, nurture regional teams, excite local and global fans, increase participation from all regions, and ensure a fair and open championship, all teams competing in the World Championship Event must meet local residency requirements. At least 60% (three out of five) Starters on any competing team must be Residents or exempt non-Residents of the region they represent in the World Championship Event. This Rule shall ensure that the goals of the World Championship Event are achieved, without undue burden on players and teams, while promoting fair play and robust competition for all participants in this global competition.

g) NA and EU LCS. The NA and EU LCS, including the NA and EU regular season and all matches leading up to the regional playoffs, are designed to identify the teams that will represent the NA and EU in the World Championship Event. In order to fulfill this mandate, all teams competing in the LCS and LCS-affiliated matches must meet the requirements in Rule 1.2(f) for teams participating in the World Championship Event, including the requirement that at least 60% (three out of five) Starters on each team be Residents of the region covered by the LCS in which they play.

h) NA and EU Challenger Series. The NA and EU Challenger Series, including the NA and EU Challenger Series regular season and all matches leading up to the Promotion Tournament, are designed to identify the teams from the NA and EU that will be promoted to the NA and EU LCS and thereby have an opportunity to represent the NA and EU in the World Championship Event. In order to fulfill this mandate, all teams competing in the Challenger Series and Challenger Series-affiliated matches must meet the requirements in Rule 1.2(f) for teams participating in the World Championship Event, including the requirement that at least 60% (three out of five) Starters on each team be Residents of the region covered by the Challenger Series in which they play.

This is the heart of the rule - having at least 3 players on every team be local to that region in some sense ensures that regional identity is preserved for a league. That principle should be reflected at every level of professional competition, from the Challenger Series all the way to representation at Worlds. Keep in mind that this specific version of the residency requirement is only going into the LCS ruleset, so it will only apply to LCS teams attending Worlds, not all Worlds-participating teams.

i) Implementation of Rule Change; Grandfathering. Any player on the Active Roster of an LCS team or a CS team who participated in the most recent Promotion Tournament at the time of this policy change who would not satisfy the Resident definition in 1.2(a) will be considered an "exempt non-resident", which allows such a player to count towards the three Residents required pursuant to Rules 1.2(f), 1.2(g), and 1.2(h). Once an exempt non-resident has met the Residency requirement, that player will be considered a Resident. A player cannot simultaneously count as a Resident for one region and as an exempt non-Resident for another region. A player can choose to waive his exempt non-Resident status in favor of counting as a Resident for another region before December 31, 11:59 pm PST 2014. In the event that a team has two or more exempt non-Resident players as Starters, they will not be permitted to add any additional non-exempt non-Residents as Starters.

This rule ensures that current LCS teams and CS teams who played in the Promotion Tournament do not have to change their rosters. In enacting the Interregional Movement Policy, it’s important to us that players already committed to playing in the region are not unduly harmed. At the same time, in the long term it’s important that changes to teams gradually move each team to a healthy balance of foreign and local talent, which is why we make the subtle distinction between Resident players and exempt non-Resident players. Allowing players to waive an exemption means that individuals who aren’t sure of the plans don’t get locked out of legitimate options. Players currently in NA can choose to waive their exemption if they would qualify as an EU resident, and vice-versa.

j) Substitutes: All teams will be required to maintain at least one Resident player as a substitute at any given time. At no point in time will teams be permitted to make a substitution which is in violation of any provision of this Rule 1.2.:

If for some reason a Starter is temporarily out of commission, we don’t want teams put in a position where they can’t field a roster in compliance with the Interregional Movement Policy. That’s why we’re requiring teams keep at least one Resident substitute on the roster as a failsafe.

k) Losing Residency: For purposes of this Rule 1.2, a player who is considered a Resident for a region will no longer be deemed to be a "Resident" of that region if such player has been primarily present in another region for 24 out of the last 36 months.

In the event that a player wants to take a break from competitive play, or has a short stint in another league that doesn’t work out, we want to make sure that they reserve the option of playing in the region where they were most recently a Resident. Giving the players the safety net of temporarily exploring options overseas without forfeiting Resident status is a priority for us, and that’s what this portion of the rule is meant to address. So, for example, an EU Resident player can join an NA team for a year, and if circumstances change and they want to go back to EU, they can do so without having lost their EU Resident status.

l) Work Eligibility: Each player must submit proof that, at the time of any LCS-affiliated match the player wishes to participate in, he/she will be (a) a legal resident of a country in their region, and (b) work-eligible in the United States (for NA players) or Germany (for EU players).

This is the same as the old residency rule: because portions of the Challenger Series and all of the LCS occur live and at a physical location, it’s important that players are present and eligible to work in the country where the event is being held.

The Interregional Movement Policy is one that benefits the overall competitive ecosystem, and other regional leagues will be incorporating something similar to the NA and EU version of the Regional Residency Requirement & Work Eligibility and releasing their equivalents at their discretion. China (LPL & LSPL), Korea (OGN The Champions, Masters & NLB), and Southeast Asia/Taiwan (GPL & LNL) handling their regional residency requirements individually. The NA and EU requirement provides a robust framework that will not only preserve regional identity in the future, but permit a healthy amount of movement between regions that is to the benefit of esports as a whole.

bios.en_US:
As the original League of Legends World Champion, Fnatic was the team to beat in LoL’s infancy. These days, the squad is completely unrecognizable from its original form. With a new roster mixing veteran playmakers like sOAZ and Rekkles plus Caps, their lone rookie, Fnatic is remaking itself. Putting their underwhelming 2016 behind them, Fnatic believe they are building a roster that could make a serious run at the EU LCS trophy.

Coach: Dylan "Dylan Falco" Falco

Team Manager: Finlay "Quaye" Stewart
bios.fr_FR:
Première détentrice du titre mondial de League of Legends, Fnatic était l'équipe à battre dans la prime enfance de LoL. Mais l'équipe d'aujourd'hui n'a plus rien à voir avec sa forme d'origine. Sa nouvelle formation accueillant à présent des talents coréens, des joueurs européens prometteurs et Rekkles, la star carry AD, Fnatic est en pleine reconstruction. Avec une série de 18 victoires sans défaite durant le segment d'été des LCS EU 2015 et une qualification pour les demi-finales du mondial 2015, l'équipe a prouvé qu'elle pouvait encore obtenir des résultats.

Coach: Dylan "Dylan Falco" Falco

Team Manager: Finlay "Quaye" Stewart
bios.pl_PL:
Legendarni obrońcy honoru Europy. Fnatic to jedna z najstarszych drużyn konkurujących w League of Legends. 14 marca 2011 roku ta organizacja, dobrze znana z udziału w innych grach, zaistniała w świecie Runeterry. Świeżo po założeniu, od razu zabrała się za największy kaliber osiągnięć. Żółto-czarni byli jedną z 8 ekip, które zakwalifikowały się do Mistrzostw Riot Games pierwszego sezonu. Dokonali tego zaledwie trzy miesiące po założeniu drużyny, co jak na początkujących, stanowiło imponujący wyczyn. Przez cały turniej przegrali tylko dwa mecze na swojej drodze do zwycięstwa. Dzięki temu osiągnięciu Europa zawdzięcza im swój jedyny dotąd mistrzowski tytuł, a codzienni gracze mogą cieszyć się skinami europejskiego zespołu. Ten historyczny triumf to był dopiero początek wielkich sukcesów tej drużyny.

Doskonałą kondycją Fnatic mógł się pochwalić również w trzecim, czwartym i piątym sezonie, podczas których reprezentował Europę na Mistrzostwach Świata. W 2014 roku nie udało im się wejść do fazy eliminacji, lecz w pozostałych latach pokazali prawdziwą klasę. Podczas MŚ w Stanach Zjednoczonych, w 2013 roku, wyszli ze swojej grupy na pierwszym miejscu, z zawrotnym wynikiem 7:1. W ćwierćfinałach podołali ówcześnie najmocniejszej drużynie Ameryki, Cloud9, na ich własnym terenie. Ulegli dopiero w półfinale z Royal Club, lecz nawet wtedy czarno-żółtym udało się zatriumfować w jednej grze przed ostateczną porażką. Podobnym powodzeniem Fnatic mógł się pochwalić podczas MŚ 2015. Kolejny raz zdominowali fazę grupową, jeszcze raz znajdując się na pierwszym miejscu, tym razem z wynikiem 4:2. W ćwierćfinale stoczyli walkę z pierwszorzędnym chińskim zespołem – Edward Gaming. Warto zauważyć, że był to jeden ze zdecydowanych faworytów tego wydarzenia. Zdominowali ich 3 do 0, nie pozostawiając cienia złudzeń co do tego, kto zasłużył na laur. Odpadli dopiero w półfinale w starciu z koreańską potęga. Patrząc na dorobek Fnatic z Mistrzostw Świata, śmiało można stwierdzić, że mało która organizacja na świecie może pochwalić się tak niezmiennie dobrymi wynikami.

O osiągnięciach tej drużyny na pomniejszych turniejach można by napisać książkę. Jednak trzeba zwrócić uwagę na bezsprzecznie niepowtarzalne triumfy zespołu Fnatic. To przede wszystkim stała i niezachwiana dominacja w lidze EU LCS. Ekipa czarno-żółtych zawsze była na pierwszym lub drugim miejscu w rozgrywkach League Championship Series. Niezłomność i permanentna obecność Fnatic na szczycie zasługuje na najwyższe uznanie. Oprócz członkostwa graczy najwyższych lotów, ten sukces wynika także z zapewnionego im troskliwego patronatu przez samą organizację. Na początku piątego sezonu do kadry dołączył Luis „Deilor” Sevilla, który wcześniej był profesjonalnym trenerem pokera. Wiele osób uważa, że w dużej mierze to właśnie on stoi za sukcesem czarno-żółtych na MŚ 2015. Pod jego opiekuńczymi skrzydłami Fnatic rozkwitło. W wiosennym sezonie EU LCS 2015 skończyli z wynikiem 13:5, a w letnim pobili światowy rekord i pozostali niepokonani aż do końca.

Coach: Dylan "Dylan Falco" Falco

Responsable d’équipe: Finlay "Quaye" Stewart
bios.de_DE:
Als LoL noch in den Kinderschuhen steckte, war Fnatic, der erste Weltmeister in der Geschichte von League of Legends, die Mannschaft, die es zu schlagen galt. Die heutige Mannschaft hat mit der damaligen nichts mehr gemein. Mit einer Mischung aus erfahrenen Spielern wie sOAZ und Rekkles sowie dem Nachwuchsspieler Caps versucht Fnatic, sich neu zu erfinden. Fnatic hat die Rückschläge des vergangenen Jahrs hinter sich gelassen und glaubt, mit der neuen Aufstellung Chancen auf den Titel in der EU LCS zu haben. Die Spieler sind entschlossen und haben das Zeug dazu, als beste Mannschaft in die langjährige Geschichte Fnatics einzugehen.

Coach: Dylan "Dylan Falco" Falco

Mannschaftsleiter: Finlay "Quaye" Stewart
bios.es_ES:
Hablar sobre Fnatic es hacerlo sobre éxito, dedicación y superación. El conjunto europeo más laureado de la escena tendrá otro año más que empezar de cero y saber renovarse para intentar emular los resultados del año pasado. Algo que se plantea casi imposible por su inmaculada temporada se tendrá que realizar con nuevos jugadores que a pesar de no ser tan desconocidos como los que comenzaron el año pasado presentan mayores dudas.

El palmarés de Fnatic es impresionante. Desde ganar el primer Campeonato Mundial de League of Legends hasta sólo perder una vez los playoffs de la LCS europea en verano de 2014 contra Alliance. La única mancha de la organización es la no presencia en el Campeonato Mundial 2012, así cómo podría considerarse un pequeño bache no pasar de la fase de grupos en el Campeonato Mundial de 2014. Pero, en el resto de ocasiones, la actuación ha sido espectacular.

Hasta el año pasado, Fnatic mantuvo un núcleo que siempre otorgaba las mismas impresiones. Durante la fase regular, probaban cambios y los resultados les dejaron un poquito al margen, pero lo suficiente como para clasificarse y luego arrasar en los playoffs. Un equipo calculador que en todo momento ha sabido aprovechar sus recursos para poder superar las expectativas de los aficionados.

El año pasado la renovación no sólo fue fructífera, sino inesperada. Los chicos de Luis ‘Deilor’ Sevilla fueron capaces de ganar en primavera después de una fase regular con sensaciones encontradas. La actuación en el Mid Season Invitational motivó a pensar que Fnatic podía plantar cara a los mejores equipos del mundo. Verano no dio lugar a dudas, puesto que ganaron todos los partidos disputados en la fase regular y estuvieron a punto de hacerlo también en los playoffs si no fuera porque Origen les plantó cara en la final y les pudo sacar dos partidos. Pero no fue suficiente, y Fnatic de nuevo se llevó el preciado trofeo.

Muchos críticos tenían curiosidad por ver si este, probablemente el mejor equipo europeo desde Moscow 5, conseguiría plantar cara a equipos internacionales. Y a pesar de un mal inicio en la fase de grupos, remontaron con un gran nivel y se clasificaron a cuartos de final. Allí derrotaron a la potencia china con una facilidad pasmosa, pero los coreanos juegan en otra división y KOO Tigers acabó con sus esperanzas en las semifinales.

Después de los mundiales tanto su top, Heo ‘Huni’ Seung-hoon, como su mid, Kim ‘Reignover’ Yeu-jin, anunciaron su intención de marcharse a américa en busca de un reto nuevo. Pero la esencia real se perdía con la marcha de Bora ‘YellOwStaR’ Kim, líder del grupo que también decidió irse con el mismo objetivo. El equipo quedó huérfano después de casi tres años enteros del francés con la organización.

Hay que mirar hacia adelante. Al igual que el año pasado las exigencias sólo eran de clasificarse al mundial y al final el buen trabajo recompensó, esta temporada hay que ser lo suficientemente humildes para poder aspirar a gestas heroicas. El equipo ha demostrado que es capaz de sacar provecho de plantillas como la actual, pero todavía es muy pronto para saber cómo funcionarán internamente y sólo queda disfrutar del progreso del conjunto.

Coach: Dylan "Dylan Falco" Falco

Jefe de equipo: Finlay "Quaye" Stewart
bios.pt_BR: O primeiro campeão mundial da história de League era o time a ser batido nos primeiros anos do cenário competitivo. Hoje, porém, a escalação é totalmente diferente daquela formação original. A nova Fnatic combina talentos coreanos com promessas do cenário europeu e uma base sólida com o suporte YellOwStaR. Eles podem estar se reconstruindo ainda, mas os resultados já são inquestionáveis: recorde de 18V-0D na etapa de verão da LCS EU, e primeiro lugar nas eliminatórias.

bios.en_US:
2016 was a rough year for ROCCAT, but they banded together when it counted. After battling their way back to the LCS in the 2016 EU LCS Summer Promotion Tournament, ROCCAT once again found themselves facing relegation after a last place finish in the Summer Split. Yet again, they narrowly escaped moving to the Challenger Series and find themselves back in the EU LCS.

ROCCAT is a different team in 2017, with only mid laner Betsy returning from the 2016 squad. With four new starters, ROCCAT will have to work to find its new identity this season.

Coach: Fabian “Grabzz” Lohmann

Team Manager: Tomislav "flyy" Mihailov
bios.pl_PL:
Niemiecka organizacja jest jedną z mniej doświadczonych formacji na najwyższym poziomie e-sportowej sceny League of Legends. Dywizja powstała w styczniu 2014 roku i przyjęła w swoje szeregi skład drużyny Kiedyś Miałem Team, któremu niespodziewanie udało się awansować do EU LCS po wygranych barażach z faworyzowanym zespołem Ninjas in Pyjamas.

W podstawowy skład drużyny wchodziło pięciu Polaków. W debiutanckim sezonie, wiośnie 2014 roku, zespół radził sobie zaskakująco dobrze, w dwóch pierwszych kolejkach wygrywając aż pięć z sześciu spotkań i stając się fenomenem rozgrywek. Ostatecznie sezon zasadniczy Team ROCCAT zakończył na wysokiej, czwartej pozycji, a w barażach zameldował się nawet na ostatnim stopniu podium, zgłaszając akces do uczestnictwa w Mistrzostwach Świata. Charakterystycznymi elementami polskiej drużyny były w tym czasie zgranie oraz umiejętność skutecznego zastosowania zaskakujących rozwiązań takich jak wybór niestandardowych bohaterów czy taktyk.

W lecie 2014 roku formacja miała nieco problemów w sezonie zasadniczym, ale w rozgrywkach barażowych powróciła do wysokiego poziomu i do końca walczyła o wyjazd na Mistrzostwa Świata, ostatecznie kończąc rywalizację na czwartej pozycji – pierwszej, która nie zapewniała awansu. Po tym dość udanym sezonie zdecydowano się na kilka zmian w składzie, które miały pomóc formacji w walce o najwyższe cele. Z drużyny odeszli „Xaxus” i „Celaver”, a ich miejsce zajęli Erlend „Nukeduck” Holm oraz Paweł „Woolite” Pruski, natomiast Overpow przeniósł się z środowej na górną aleję. Formacja w odświeżonym składzie zaprezentowała się katastrofalnie w wiosennym sezonie 2015, bardzo długo walcząc o pozostanie w EU LCS i ostatecznie zapewniając sobie miejsce w elicie dopiero po wygranych barażach. Zmieniona ekipa w żadnym stopniu nie spełniła oczekiwań i nie była w stanie nawiązać walki o czołowe lokaty w europejskich rozgrywkach, wobec czego kolejne roszady w składzie nie były niczym zaskakującym. Z drużyną pożegnał się krytykowany „Overpow”, który nie sprawdził się w nowej roli, a jego miejsce zajął Etienne „Steve” Michels, który początkowo spisywał się niewiele lepiej od swojego poprzednika. Miejsce w zespole zachował ostatecznie bardzo zawodzący na wiosnę „Woolite”.

Jednakże drużyna nadal nie przekonywała i rywalizowała raczej o uniknięcie relegacji, aniżeli o miejsce w górnej części tabeli. W związku z tym w połowie letniego sezonu 2015 także „Woolite” opuścił zespół. Na jego miejsce przybył występujący w tym czasie w Challenger Series Rasmus „MrRallez” Skinneholm. Nie poprawiło to gry drużyny z dnia na dzień, ale ostatecznie Team ROCCAT awansował do baraży, gdzie jednak szybko odpadł z rywalizacji, przegrywając ćwierćfinałowy pojedynek z Unicorns of Love. Niemniej drużynie udało się dostać do turnieju kwalifikacyjnego na Mistrzostwa Świata, gdzie formacja zdobyła się jeszcze na ostatni zryw i pokazała się z dobrej strony. Do końca walczyła o bilety na najważniejsze zawody sezonu, ostatecznie przegrywając 2¬ 3 z późniejszymi półfinalistami światowego czempionatu – Origen.

Po sezonie 2015 w zespole doszło do prawdziwego trzęsienia ziemi. Szybko pożegnano się ze „Stevem” i „MrRallezem”, którzy swoimi występami nie przekonali włodarzy ekipy i zostali wypożyczeni do Elements. Niestety organizacji nie udało się zatrzymać także „Jankosa” i „Vandera”, a w związku z tym z zespołu odszedł również „Nukeduck”. Wobec tego w wiosennym sezonie 2016 można było zobaczyć całkowicie odmieniony Team ROCCAT. Kolejny, wiosenny sezon EU LCS 2016 również poszedł nie po myśli organizacji Team ROCCAT. Drużyna skończyła na przedostatniej pozycji z wynikiem 4 do 14, więc była zaledwie o jedno zwycięstwo lepsza od zespołu na ostatnim miejscu. W związku z takim obrotem spraw Team ROCCAT trafił do rozgrywek relegacyjnych. Tam drużyna stanęła na wysokości zadania – zwyciężyła 3 do 1 z zespołem Huma, więc zachowała swoje miejsce w prestiżowej lidze. Po tym okresie Team ROCCAT zdecydowała się na kolejną gruntowną reorganizację drużyny. Dlatego zdecydowała się na zakontraktowanie dwóch Koreańczyków, na podobieństwo innych organizacji. Uzupełnieniem dla debiutantów z Korei została francuska gwiazda - strzelec Pierre "steeelback" Medjaldi. Zatem pomimo załamań Team ROCCAT rozpoczęła letni sezon EU LCS 2016 z podniesioną głową, gotowa na wszystkie wyzwania.

Coach: Fabian "Grabzz" Lohmann

Menedżer drużyny: Tomislav "flyy” Mihailov
bios.de_DE:
2016 war ein schweres Jahr für ROCCAT, aber die Mannschaft rückte in den entscheidenden Momenten zusammen. Nachdem sich ROCCAT im Sommer-Aufstiegsturnier 2016 wieder in die LCS gekämpft hatte, mussten sie nach dem letzten Platz im Sommer-Split gleich wieder zurück in die Relegation. Doch sie schafften es erneut, der Challenger Series knapp zu entgehen und in der EU LCS zu bleiben. 2017 ist ROCCAT bis auf den Mid-Laner Betsy eine neue Mannschaft. Mit vier neuen Spielern, zu denen auch ein unerfahrener Supporter und Top-Laner gehören, wird ROCCAT hart arbeiten müssen, um während des Frühjahrs-Splits eine neue Identität zu finden.

Coach: Fabian „Grabzz“ Lohmann

Mannschaftsleiter: Tomislav "flyy” Mihailov
bios.es_ES:
ROCCAT accedió a la LCS EU en 2014, cuando compraron el equipo Kiedyś Miałem Team, una escuadra polaca formada en 2012 para competir en el torneo de promoción europeo. ROCCAT tuvo un ascenso meteórico en su primera temporada, llegando a los playoffs de ambos Splits de la LCS, tanto primavera como verano, y era considerado como uno de los mejores equipos de la región. No obstante, una decepcionante actuación en el Split de primavera de 2015 dejó grandes sombras acerca del futuro del equipo. 2016 es un nuevo comienzo para ROCCAT, con una alineación completamente nueva intentará demostrar que puede volver a luchar por todo.

Coach: Fabian "Grabzz" Lohmann

Jefe de equipo: Tomislav "flyy” Mihailov
bios.fr_FR:
ROCCAT est arrivée aux LCS EU en 2014 en acquérant la formation de Kiedyś Miałem Team, une équipe polonaise créée en 2012 pour participer au tournoi de promotion EU. Après s'être qualifiée pour les play-offs des LCS EU lors des segments du printemps et d'été dès sa première saison, ROCCAT était considérée comme l'une des meilleures nouvelles équipes d'Europe. Des performances décevantes durant le segment printanier 2015 ont cependant mis son avenir en péril. ROC espère que sa toute nouvelle formation sera le changement qu'il lui fallait pour retrouver sa gloire d'antan.

Coach : Fabian "Grabzz" Lohmann

Responsable d’équipe: Tomislav "flyy” Mihailov

Millenium est l’équipe française avec le plus grand palmarès. Depuis la création de la structure professionnelle en 2011, elle aligne une équipe compétitive toujours plus ambitieuse. En 2016, elle s’est notamment hissée sur la plus haute marche du podium de la quasi totalité des compétitions du pays, notamment du Challenge France. Après une remise en question et une toute nouvelle composition autour du midlaner Pretty, Millenium affiche clairement ses ambitions : le titre de champion de France et une victoire en Challenger Series pour rejoindre le circuit professionnel des LCS.

bios.en_US:
H2K entered the 2016 World Championship as underdogs. They left as the best team from the west. After an up and down performance in the 2016 EU LCS Summer Split, H2K qualified for Worlds on Championship Points. Jankos led the charge to silence the doubters, and H2K made it all the way to the Semifinal round against Samsung Galaxy.

Just when Europe seemed its weakest, H2K showed what they could accomplish on the international stage. With a reworked roster for 2017, they’ll work to earn another spot at Worlds to try and make it even closer to the championship and make their region proud.

Coach: Neil “Pr0lly” Hammad

Team Manager: Javier "J.ZAFRA" Zafra
bios.fr_FR:
La structure H2K a commencé ses activités sur League of Legends en 2011. De nombreux joueurs talentueux comme Johannes « puszu » Uibos, Remigiusz « Overpow » Pusch ou Sebastian « niQ » Robak ont fait étape dans cette structure basée au Royaume-Uni, sans résultats significatifs. C’est en juin 2014 que l’organisation passe à la vitesse supérieure en recrutant quatre anciens de Cloud9 Eclipse : le toplaner roumain Andrei « Odoamne » Pascu, le jungler danois Jonas « Trashy » Andersen, le midlaner néerlandais Fabian « Febiven » Diepstraten et le carry AD suédois Petter « Hjärnan » Freyschuss, rejoints par le support roumain Baltat « AoD » Alin. Ce nouveau collectif remporte les Challengers series mais échoue à se qualifier aux LCS lors du tournoi de promotion. L’aventure aurait pu s’arrêter sur cet échec, mais deux nouvelles places sont mises en jeu dans le cadre de l’augmentation du nombre d’équipes prenant part aux League of Legends Championship Series.

Afin de se préparer au mieux à cette nouvelle échéance, H2K recrute le Français Jean-Victor « loulex » Burgevin pour remplacer Trashy, ainsi que l’Estonien Erih « Voidle » Sommermann, qui retrouve ses ex-coéquipiers et prend la place laissée vacante par AoD. L’ancien joueur professionnel Neil « Pr0lly » Hammad est lui importé des États-Unis pour assurer la fonction de coach. La mayonnaise prend et H2K parvient finalement à se hisser aux LCS ! Febiven reçoit alors une offre de Fnatic, qu’il ne peut pas refuser. Pour palier son départ, H2K fait appel aux services du Coréen Sang-ook « Ryu » Yoo, récemment arrivé en Europe.

Les débuts aux LCS sont difficiles. Lors de la semaine 3, H2K compte 2 victoires pour 4 défaites et occupe la 7e place du classement provisoire. Voidle est alors écarté et Raymond « kaSing » Tsang est appelé pour le remplacer. L’arrivée du Londonien est salvatrice : H2K enchaîne 8 victoires consécutives et remonte le classement jusqu’à atteindre une 3e place qu’elle ne quitte plus, même lors des play-offs. L’équipe joue un jeu calme et calculé dans lequel Hjärnan est le carry principal tandis que Ryu est adepte des assassins. L’impact de Pr0lly dans cette réussite est récompensé quand il obtient le titre de meilleur coach. En saison estivale, H2K réitère et obtient à nouveau la 3e place de la saison régulière et des play-offs. Grâce aux points de circuit, l’équipe est qualifiée pour le mondial mais tombe dans un groupe C au niveau très relevé dont elle ne parvient pas à sortir.

Après une année 2015 d’un très bon cru, H2K reconstruit son équipe autour de deux joueurs qui ont beaucoup contribué à la réussite du collectif, Ryu et Odoamne. Le Polonais Marcin « Jankos » Jankowski (qui a déjà évolué chez H2K en 2013) prend le relais au poste de jungler tandis que le Grec Konstantinos « FORG1VENGRE » Tzortziou-Napoleon et le Polonais Oskar « Vander » Bogdan constituent la nouvelle voie du bas. Pour accompagner cette équipe, H2K recrute l’analyste Michael « Veteran » Archer, qui a déjà travaillé avec Origen, ainsi que Oliver « IzpAH » Steer, qui a été manager pour Fnatic pendant plusieurs années. La première apparition de cette nouvelle composition se fait aux Intel Extreme Masters et se solde par une victoire convaincante face à Cloud9 et une défaite contre les Coréens de Ever, des résultats somme toute encourageants étant donné le peu de temps d’entraînement dont disposait l’équipe.

Coach: Neil "Pr0lly" Hammad

Responsable d’équipe: Javier "J.ZAFRA" Zafra
bios.pl_PL:
H2k to jedna z najstarszych organizacji League of Legends w Europie. Powstała jeszcze w styczniu 2011 roku, ale długo nie potrafiła nawiązać walki z czołowymi zespołami z regionu. W latach 2011-2013 formacja odnosiła sukcesy głównie na mniejszych turniejach, a przez jej szeregi przewinęło się wielu interesujących zawodników, którzy później stanowili o sile regionu jak choćby Maik „MoMa” Wallus, Erlend „Nukeduck” Holm, Johannes „puszu” Uibos czy skład znany później jako Kiedyś Miałem Team, a następnie – Team ROCCAT. Żaden z wymienionych graczy nie związał się jednak z organizacją na dłużej i prędzej czy później odchodził.

Przełom nastąpił w połowie 2014 roku, kiedy H2k zdecydowało się zatrudnić skład byłej europejskiej dywizji Cloud9. Do Andreia „Odoamne” Pascu, Fabiana „Febivena” Diepstratena, Jonasa „Trashy’ego” Andersena i Pettera "Hjärnana" Freyschussa dołączył także nowy wspierający z Rumunii - Baltat „AoD” Alin, którego jednak szybko zastąpił Belg Bram „wewillfailer” de Winter. Zespół doskonale poradził sobie w EU Challenger Series, wygrywając jedną z letnich edycji rozgrywek 2014. Ostatecznie drużynie udało się zwyciężyć także w decydującym turnieju i przystąpić do baraży, ale porażka w starciu z Copenhagen Wolves znów odsunęła plany dołączenia do elitarnych rozgrywek. Nie wszystko było jednakże stracone, bowiem EU LCS rozszerzało ilość uczestników, a dodatkowy turniej miał wyłonić dwa dodatkowe zespoły.

W międzyczasie w zespole szybko doszło do rotacji, w wyniku których z formacją pożegnali się Trashy i wewillfailer, a w ich miejsce przybyli Jean-Victor „loulex” Burgevin oraz Erih „Voidle” Sommermann. H2k było niewątpliwie jednym z murowanych faworytów Expansion Tournamentu i nie zawiodło, całkowicie miażdżąc konkurencję (3:0 z n!faculty i 3:0 z GIANTS) i awansując do EU LCS.

Wtedy pojawiły się kolejne problemy, bo ofertę Fnatic przyjął najważniejszy zawodnik drużyny – midlaner Fabian „Febiven” Diepstraten. Zastąpił go utytułowany Koreańczyk Yoo “Ryu” Sang-ook, który jednak zdawał się mieć swoje najlepsze czasy za sobą… H2k rozpoczęło wiosenny split dość przeciętnie, ale dołączenie do zespołu Raymonda „KaSinga” Tsanga w miejsce Voidle’a zupełnie odmieniło drużynę, która zanotowała fenomenalną passę ośmiu zwycięstw z rzędu. Formacja ostatecznie skończyła zmagania na trzeciej pozycji w sezonie zasadniczym i na tym samym miejscu zameldowała się w play-offach. Świetny dla H2k okres miał swój dalszy ciąg w lecie, kiedy to formacja obroniła trzecią lokatę i dostała się na Mistrzostwa Świata dzięki Championship Points.

Tam zespół trafił niestety do grupy z dwoma najwyżej notowanymi zespołami z Korei i Chin – SKT T1 oraz Edward Gaming. Pomimo, że europejska drużyna była z miejsca skazywana na porażkę, powalczyła jeszcze z faworyzowanymi rywalami, choć i tak odpadła z turnieju już po fazie grupowej.

Przerwa między sezonem 2015 a 2016 była dla drużyny bardzo burzliwa. Ekipę opuściło aż trzech graczy: KaSing, Hjärnan oraz loulex. H2k całkowicie przebudowało zespół, godnie zastępując swoich byłych już zawodników. W ich miejsce dołączyli bowiem wyróżniający się gracze Teamu ROCCAT: Oskar „Vander” Bogdan, Marcin „Jankos” Jankowski, a także znakomity, grecki strzelec – Konstantinos „FORG1VEN” Tzortziou.

Coach: Neil “Pr0lly” Hammad

Team Manager: Javier "J.ZAFRA" Zafra
bios.de_DE:
H2K fuhr als Außenseiter zur Weltmeisterschaft 2016. Und sie kamen als beste westliche Mannschaft wieder zurück. Nach einer durchwachsenen Vorstellung im Sommer-Split der EU LCS 2016 qualifizierte sich H2K über die Meisterschaftspunkte für die Weltmeisterschaft. Unter der Leitung von Jankos ließ H2K alle Kritiker verstummen und traf im Halbfinale der Weltmeisterschaft auf Samsung Galaxy. Gerade als Europa am Boden zu liegen schien, stellte H2K seine Qualitäten auf der internationalen Bühne unter Beweis. Mit einer neuen Aufstellung werden sie 2017 versuchen, sich erneut für die Weltmeisterschaft zu qualifizieren, um dort dem Weltmeistertitel noch näher zu kommen und ihre Region stolz zu machen.

Coach: Neil “Pr0lly” Hammad

Mannschaftsleiter: Javier "J.ZAFRA" Zafra
bios.es_ES:
H2K se ganó un puesto en la LCS gracias al Expansion Tournament europeo en 2014. Su debut en la LCS EU fue todo un éxito, ya que consiguieron un récord de 12 victorias frente a 6 derrotas durante la temporada regular, lo que los posicionó en el tercer puesto. H2K continuó su potente temporada inicial y consiguió otro tercer puesto en la LCS EU 2015.

En el split de primavera de 2016 también hizo una actuación admirable, pero flaquearon en los playoffs, lo que les hizo perder el tercer puesto contra Fnatic. La historia se repetiría en el split de verano, cuando H2K se derrumbó ante Splyce en un enfrentamiento al mejor de cinco en el que se disputaron todas las partidas. Por suerte para H2K, se clasificaron para el Mundial gracias a los puntos de campeonato. Aun habiendo perdido contra Splyce, H2K se mostró seguro con el experto veterano Konstantinos ''FORG1VEN'' Tzortziou-Napoleon, quien propició lo que parecía otro split perdido. El grupo se clasifica para el Mundial como claros perdedores, pero ¿quién sabe? Quizás este sea el año en que H2K ayude a recuperar el trofeo que Europa perdió hace tanto tiempo.

Entrenador: Neil ''Pr0lly'' Hammad

Jefe de equipo: Javier "J.ZAFRA" Zafra
bios.pt_BR:
A H2K ganhou sua vaga na LCS através do Torneio de Expansão da EU em 2014. Sua estreia na EU LCS foi um sucesso, alcançando um recorde de 12V-6D no percurso da temporada regular e conquistando o 3º lugar. A H2K continuou sua forte estreia na temporada com mais um 3º lugar na EU LCS em 2015.

A equipe mais uma vez teve um desempenho admirável durante a Etapa de Primavera 2016, mas fraquejaram nas Eliminatórias, perdendo o 3º lugar para a Fnatic. Mas a história se repetiu na Etapa de Verão e a H2K foi derrotada mais uma vez pela Splyce em uma melhor de 5. Felizmente para a H2K, eles conseguiram se qualificar para o Mundial através de seus Pontos de Campeonato. Mesmo depois de sua perda para a Splyce, a H2K voltou de cabeça erguida depois do veterano Konstantinos “FORG1VEN” Tzortziou-Napoleon ter arrancado o que parecia ser outra Etapa perdida. A equipe vai para o Mundial claramente como azarões, mas quem sabe... Talvez este ano, a H2K possa ajudar a Europa a finalmente recuperar o seu troféu.
